%p OpenGovernment is a freeÂ and open-source public resource website for government transparency at the state and local levels. The site is a non-partisan joint project of two non-profit organizations, the <a href="http://www.participatorypolitics.org/">Participatory Politics Foundation</a> and the <a href="http://sunlightfoundation.com/">Sunlight Foundation</a>, and is independent from any government entity, candidate for office, or political party.

%p OpenGovernment comes to you from the team that brought you OpenCongress.org, a leading web resource for civic engagement. Conceived in 2004, the main problem that OpenCongress sought to address was a lack of accessible information online about bills, votes, and issues in the U.S. Congress. The official website of Congress, Thomas.loc.gov, published raw data about legislation, but not in open data standards, not in timely ways, and not on webpages that were sufficiently user-friendly. (More than 15 years after Thomas' launch, it still doesn't come close to doing any of these things, which is unacceptable.)

%p OpenCongress addressed this problem, as much as possible given inherited technical limitations imposed by the data sources, by combining official government information with social wisdom from around the open Web. The resulting open-source software on OpenCongress enables individuals and organizations to track and share information about what's really happening in Congress through a user-friendly web application. Since its launch in 2007, OpenCongress has grown to become the most-visited government transparency website in the United States, and is proud to be an active contributor to a burgeoning ecosystem of open-government resources online. 

%p Writing in late 2010, the situation with official websites for U.S. state legislatures is nearly exactly as with Thomas in 2004. Unfortunately, almost no U.S. state government makes its data available in full online. Out of the 49 bicameral state legislatures in the U.S. and one unicameral body (Nebraska's), only one chamber -- one entity out of 99, namely the New York State Senate -- makes its legislative data available in ways that are sufficiently compliant with the community-generated 8 Principles of Open Government Data. Every other chamber of state government remains insistently closed-off from its constituents, refusing to release data (actions, votes, bill analysis -- don't even get us started on campaign contributions) online for all to see, despite the proven technical means to do so. And that's just to address the "defective by design" state of the back-end data that power what the public has the misfortune to occasionally try to encountner ... on the front-end, the status quo for state-level government web presences is a mishmash of non-standards-based, under-resourced, almost-hilariously poorly-designed websites that don't do nearly enough to informing the public at large. Public data can and should be public, immediately and in full, and it can and should be made accessible to everyone online, so as to increase trust and civic engagement in our representative democracy. 

%p OpenGovernment is a first step towards a solution. The ultimate mission of OpenGovernment is to achieve full public transparency in all three branches of government (executive, legislative, and judicial) at every level of our representative democracy (federal, state, city, local, and more). In the shorter-term, OpenGovernment is basically a version of OpenCongress for state legislatures, in early open-source development. We cleaned-up the OC code base for OG, bringing over some parts and writing lots of new code, making it better-documented and more modular. We also simplified the web design and foregrounded more of our user-friendly participation tools along with our unique data offerings. We offer OpenGovernment to the public commons as a free, libre, and open-source model for open standards and future government transparency projects -- contributions warmly welcomed and remixes encouraged. 

%p As of October 2010, OpenGovernment has information for five state legislatures: California, Louisiana, Maryland, Texas, and Wisconsin. (Why these five states? The shortest answer is: these data problems are gnarly to solve, and it made sense for technical reasons to start with these five, including two of the three biggest most-populous states in the country in CA and TX.) Over the course of the next year, we seek to roll out OpenGovernment to the remaining 45 U.S. state legislatures, and with additional resources, to more than a dozen major cities across the country. If you live in one of these five states, register a free account with OpenGovernment to get started and connect with your elected officials. If you don't live in one of these five states, you can still register a free account, as a version of OpenGovernment for your state is in the works and coming your way within a year -- <a href="/pages/help"> you can help</a> speed it along and make it better, and until then you can explore our current offerings. We love questions and feedback, let us know what you think! <a href="/pages/contact">Contact us.</a>

